        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The 15NNH+ and N15NH+ (1-0) lines will be both observed in Baseband-1 with two spectral windows of 117 MHz, and a spectral resolution of 0.122 MHz (i.e. ~0.4 km/s). This resolution will be enough to resolve the shape of both lines (Fig. 2, right). In Baseband-2, we will observe N2H+ (1-0) with 0.2 km/s resolution to derive an accurate fit to the hyperfine structure, needed to estimate the line opacity and excitation temperature accurately. A spectral window of 343 km/s and a spectral resolution of ~0.354 km/s will be placed in Baseband-3 on the J=6-5 K-ladder of the CH3CCH molecule, which is a well-known good thermometer in dense gas (Fontani et al. 2002). Baseband-4 will be used at the worse angular resolution for continuum.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>From Fig. 2 (left) in the Scientific Justification, one can see that the emission has a clumpy morphology, with total size expected to be as large as 15-20'', while the size of the dense condensations is about 3-5''. Therefore, the requested angular resolution of 2'' is sufficient to resolve the dense cores. Such a resolution can be achieved at 91 GHz with the 12-m array in C36-2 configuration, which will provide a Maximum Recoverable Scale of 25'', i.e. appropriate to recover the expected extended structures. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The peak temperature (in T_MB) in the IRAM-30m spectrum of the faintest transition (namely 15NNH+1-0) is ~0.05 K, corresponing to a flux density of ~0.25 Jy. Based on the emission detected with the IRAM PdBI at 2 mm (Fig. 2, left, Lopez-Sepulcre et al. 2013), one can assume a source size of ~10''. This means that the flux density expected in a 2'' beam is 0.25*(2/10)^2 ~ 0.01 Jy. The line widths are about 2 km/s. Therefore, a channel width of 0.4 km/s is sufficient to resolve the lines. With these assumptions, under standard weather conditions, at 91 GHz we will achieve a 1 sigma rms of 2 mJy in 2.29 hours (4 hours including overheads), providing a S/N~5.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
