        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In Baseband-1 we will place a spectral window of ~450 km/s and a spectral resolution of ~0.2 km/s to image the N2D+ (2-1) line, sufficient to resolve the hyperfine structure of the line (see Fig. 2 in the Scientific Justification). An equal spectral window will be placed in Baseband-2 to image the CH3CCH J=9-8 K ladder, which will be used to derive the gas temperature together with the lines of the same molecule observed at 3mm. A spectral window with the worst spectral resolution will be placed in Baseband-3 to image the continuum, and in Baseband-4 we will place a spectral window of 490 km/s and spectral resolution of 0.25 km/s to image the C34S (3-2) line.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To compare the N2D+ and N2H+/15NNH+ observations, we plan to obtain a map in the same configuration of the 12.m array used for the observations at 3mm (i.e. C36-2). The maps will be then smoothed at the same angular resolution. The maximum angular scale recoverable at 154 GHz in this configuration is ~17'', i.e. comparable to the largest extended structure expected (15-20'').</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>In the IRAM-30m ASAI spectrum of the N2D+(2-1) line, the peak temperature us 0.5 K (Fig. 2, right), corresponding to a peak flux density of ~2.8 Jy. Assuming a flat emission in a region of ~10'' (see Fig. 2, left, in the Scientific Justification), the flux density expected in a 1.2'' beam is ~50 mJy. Assuming also a spectral resolution of ~0.2 km/s (enough to resolve the line hyperfine structure), we request an rms of 5 mJy to have an excellent S/N of 10. This rms can be achieved, assuming the conditions above and standard weather conditions at 154 GHz, in 27 mins on source (57 mins including overheads).</prj:justificationText>
