    <prp:abstract>The two stable less abundant isotopes of hydrogen and nitrogen, D and 15N, are both enriched in comets and carbonaceous chondrites with respect to the values measured in the proto-solar nebula. This raises the question whether the two enrichments have a common origin, and how both are linked to the past chemical history of the Solar System. Low-angular resolution observations of N2H+ isotopologues (N2D+, 15NNH+ and N15NH+) toward precursors of rich clusters (similar to the environment in which our Sun was born), suggest a faint anti-correlation between the H/D and 14N/15N ratio. But since such faint anti-correlation is based on low-angular resolution spectra of the sources, known to have complex morphology, firm conlusions are impossible. We propose to investigate the spatial (anti-)correlation between H/D and 14N/15N in the best proto-cluster precursor of Solar-like Systems: OMC2-FIR4. We plan to image N2H+, 15NNH+, and N15NH+ (1-0) and N2D+(2-1) with ALMA with the appropriate angular resolution (~2''). The results of this project will allow to unveil for the first time a possible link between the isotope fractionation of two of the most important elements in the universe</prp:abstract>
